  "prompt": "At what point does the cost of bringing up a child (childcare+opportunity cost) will disincentivise a couple not to have it?",
  "response": "This is a complex issue that varies greatly depending on several factors:\n\n1. Geographic Location\n- Cost of living differs dramatically\n- Childcare costs vary by region/country\n- Societal support systems (subsidies, parental leave)\n\n2. Economic Factors\n- Household income\n- Career prospects\n- Local job market\n- Cost of education\n- Healthcare expenses\n\n3. Personal Considerations\n- Career interruption (especially for women)\n- Lost earning potential\n- Professional trajectory\n- Individual career ambitions\n\nRough Estimated Costs (US example):\n- Birth/Delivery: $10-30k\n- First year expenses: $20-30k\n- Childcare (age 0-5): $50-100k\n- Education (K-12): $100-200k\n- College: $100-300k\n\nTotal Estimated Lifetime Cost: $280-660k per child\n\nBreaking Point Factors:\n- Household income below $75-100k\n- High urban living costs\n- Limited career flexibility\n- Lack of family support\n- High personal career investment\n\nPsychological Threshold:\n- When perceived financial/career stress > perceived emotional fulfillment\n\nNo universal number - highly individualized decision based on personal circumstances.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect?",
